@Binchan: Oh my goodness. They also used Chinese characters as postpositional particles for Korean grammar like hiragana style since AD 4~6! It's called [Idu](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idu_script) script or [Hyangchal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyangchal). 

I think [Baekje](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baekje) and Japanese dynasty at that time must have been exchanging messages in those scripts. Amazing.

@caryoscelus: There're more syllables in 한글 hundreds years ago, but lost some of them as well as pronunciations of certain syllables. (ㅐ sounds weaker than ㅔ which is usually placed in the postposition like に in 日本語 rather than used in the words.)
> which makes it harder to apply to different languages.
You can re-summon unused alphabets from ancient 한글 for substitutions of non-korean languages such as 'th'ree, ca'r', Ba'ch', etc. We construct a single syllable 한[han] with three sounds ㅎ[h]+ㅏ[a]+ㄴ[n], but it's not required for other languages. They can be written "ㅎㅏㄴ". Then it becomes no difference from english-latin alphabets except easier to remember and learn. But building each independent syllable by assembling 2 to 3 sounds has its own benefits anyway.

> Hangul in Indonesia failed.[39] But there are still some people that use Hangul at home or co-officially.
@Binchan: The main reasons are two. One is that those idiot Koreans offered the natives a constructive syllable assembling method (ex. 한) in writing and reading. They should have offered a listing or serializing sounds method (ex. ㅎㅏㄴ). Another is that they should have made an internet community like Zeronet to make the natives to type and read the useful information and news among them frequently. 
Anyway, Indonesian government admits only latin characters in every official writing as a law, so there's no way to make 한글 as an official character or teaching course in that place.

